Date: 1 Nov 2001
From: Michael A. Sauri, MD <sauri@ix.netcom.com> [edited

Response to Previous Comments
-----------------------------
Dr. Mark Buller's comments have intrigued me enough to systematically
review a decade of vaccinia immunizations (about 1000) that I have given in
my clinic. From the beginning I used an entry form that can specifically
answer the question of durability of immunity to vaccinia vaccine based on
"re-challenging" the individual with the vaccine. The form religiously
recorded the demographic data of the vaccinee, the history (and their age)
of previous immunization, the presence of a validating scar, the number of
sticks given, the type of reaction (primary, vaccinoid, or immune) noted at
7 days, any complications, the lot number, the vaccinator, and all dates to
determine time intervals between the previous immunization and the current
immunization.
It is because of this systematic method used from the beginning in my
clinic that I could confidently state some personal observations with the
other members of ProMED-mail. I will attempt to publish the findings as
soon as possible.
--
Michael A. Sauri, MD, MPH&TM, FACP, FACPM
9715 Medical Center Drive
Suite 201
Rockville, MD 20850
