From: Dan Michaeli, MD <michaeli@netvision.net.il> [edited

Published Information on Immunity after Smallpox Vaccination
----------------------------------------------------------
In their book "Smallpox Cholera" (Abaccus press, Tunbridge Wells, Kent,
1977 ) Tudor and Strati give the following information, which is relevant
to the issue of the protective effect of vaccination over the years (p.
151): "In terms of the interval elapsing after the primary vaccination the
risk of smallpox is:
(i) 1:1000 after 1 year;
(ii) 1:200 after 3 years;
(iii) 1:8 after 10 years;
(iv) 1:2 after 20 years."
They also mention that: "Although the risk of contracting the disease is
fairly good the mortality rate is very small even after many years ...
Emergency re-vaccination on the outbreak of an epidemic, in a community
vaccinated many years before is far more efficient...". And on p. 154: "
When the danger of infection increases, vaccination must be extended to
groups of the population which are usually exempt from vaccination, and
must be carried out under the protection of specific immunoglobulin or drugs."
In the book "The Eradication of Smallpox from India" of Basu, Jezek & Ward,
WHO Regional Publications South-East Asia Series No.5, New Delhi, 1979, p.
111, [it is stated that: "The rates of Post Vaccination Encephalitis
ranged between 0.16 to 1.47 per 10 000 000 vaccinations."
In Christie's "Infectious Diseases Epidemiology and Clinical Practice,"
Williams & Wilkinson ed., Baltimore, 1969 p.222, [it is stated that: "For
at least 10 years there is complete protection against death, and
substantial protection against attack..."
--
Dan Michaeli, MD
Clalit Health Services, Israel
<michaeli@ netvision.net.il>
<michaeli@clalit.org.il>
